{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488296"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:36:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:36:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"405"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/405"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.41,0.02,0.15,0.33]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"405"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"20854"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/405"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"405"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"10009"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"242"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5476"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31314"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"20854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/20854"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 65-year-old woman presents with a painless lesion on the dorsal aspect of her left wrist (Image). This has been present for several months and is slowly increasing in size. She finds its size and position a nuisance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fine needle aspiration cytology","Excision","Plain X-ray","Drainage","Ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a ganglion. There are a variety of causes for ganglions, including mucoid degeneration and trauma.  Some are associated with degenerative joint disease. The diagnosis can usually be made on a clinical basis alone and investigations such as fine need aspiration cytology of imaging would only be done in cases of diagnostic doubt. If the ganglion does not bother the patient, it can be left well alone. In this case, the lump is beginning to bother the patient and some form of treatment should be offered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA ganglion cyst can be aspirated; either aspirated alone or associated with injection of prednisolone. In either case, two-thirds of the cysts will have refilled within twelve months. The most effective treatment is formal \u003Cstrong\u003Eexcision\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ganglion cysts are best treated by excision."],"references":["Gant J, Ruff M, Janz BA. Wrist Ganglions JHS \u20022011; 36"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"10009"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"405"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14115"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14115"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c0c578eb-cbf5-4bcc-91d8-b63cb3201346.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c0c578eb-cbf5-4bcc-91d8-b63cb3201346.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"10009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/10009"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-02-12T13:01:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-25T16:41:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"405"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"20854"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/